<TITLE> Russia offers to ease curbs on election monitors </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Feb 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russia on Tuesday offered to ease restrictions imposed on Europe's main election watchdog by giving its monitors a week longer to observe the March 2 presidential poll, Russian news agencies said. "We expect the mission from the OSCE (Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe) to start work on Feb. 20," Interfax news agency quoted Central Election Commission member Igor Borisov as saying. Russia previously told OSCE monitors they could start work only three days ahead of the election. The monitors said they needed to come three weeks early week to observe the vote properly. Russia also extended the number of monitors invited from the OSCE's election observation body, ODIHR, to 75 from 70. An ODIHR spokesman declined to comment on the Russian proposal. ODIHR pulled out of monitoring Russia's Dec. 2 parliamentary election because it said restrictions prevented it from properly doing its job. Russia accused the United States of putting pressure on the Warsaw-based organisation to pull out of the Dec. 2 election and has already said ODIHR is trying to sabotage monitoring plans for the March presidential vo
